(1) The use of ‘Scotland’, ‘Scottish’ or ‘of Scotland’ in your proposed name implies a connection with the Scottish Government, a government department or a local or specified public authority. This applies even if the word is a surname. The situation of the company’s registered office must be in Scotland. If you decide to resubmit your application you must provide a letter or email of non-objection from the Scottish Government or relevant body. This applies even if the word is a surname; AND/OR (2) If you wish to use ‘Scotland’ or ‘Scottish’ as the first word in your proposed name or ‘of Scotland’ anywhere in the name, you will need to demonstrate that the company is pre-eminent or very substantial in its field. You will also need to provide independent support from a representative body, trade association or other relevant organisation. The registered office or in the case of a business name, the principal place of business, must be in Scotland. For use in a business name, you must confirm the location of the principal place of business. We are unable to accept incorporation applications via the Web Incorporation Service if the company name contains a sensitive word or phrase. If you wish to re-file your application with supporting evidence, please file on paper or use a formation agent. See our website for details. We apologise for any inconvenience caused.

You will also need to provide independent support from a representative body, trade association or other relevant body. If ‘Britain’ or ‘British’ is not the first word in your proposed name it will normally be accepted. The word THE is not counted as a first word when company names are considered as a whole. If you wish to use ‘Britain’ or ‘British’ because it is a surname, you will normally be given approval if the proposed name includes forenames or initials.
